    <hr />
    <h4><span>Assessment of Current Stress Levels</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >In this section, we find an assessment of an employee&#x27;s current
        stress levels - ranked from
      </span><strong><span>Outstanding </span></strong><span>to </span><strong
        ><span>Terrible. </span></strong
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Stress impacts every part of life - including a life at Lumon. Even the
        simplest of tasks can feel overwhelming when stress is mismanaged. We
        want employees and teams to address stressful situations before problems
        arise. To that end, HR has identified the solution: constant assessment.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Generally speaking, stress impacts one&#x27;s ability to successfully
        take action. For the purposes of the
      </span><strong><span>LIEP</span></strong><span>
        document, we depict this condition as an increase in &quot;stress
        points&quot; incurred by an employee - one check filled in for each
        point of stress gained.
      </span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Most stress is fleeting of course. As a result, one point of stress may
        be wiped clean from the document on a daily basis. The rejuvenation that
        comes with every morning&#x27;s re-entering onto the Lumon severed floor
        has been proven to have lasting effects on our employee&#x27;s sense of
        well being.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Please note that assessing stress continually using your
      </span><strong><span>LIEP</span></strong><span>
        is required by all employees!</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h4><span>Stress Related Circumstances</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >Some forms of stress are significant enough to instead constitute as
      </span><strong><span>Problems</span></strong><span
        >, with a capital &quot;P&quot;. A
      </span><strong><span>Problem</span></strong><span>
        is a stress-inducing circumstance that cannot be resolved without
        intervention.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>A </span><strong><span>Problem </span></strong><span
        >can look like many things, such as tension between an employee and
        their manager, the fallout incurred from a missed deadline, or an
        inter-departmental grudge derived from a team mixer gone wrong.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>If a </span><strong><span>Problem</span></strong><span>
        is identified, write a &quot;P&quot; into the left-most stress checkbox
        in the
      </span><strong><span>Assessment of Current Stress Levels</span></strong
      ><span> section. If a </span><strong><span>Serious Problem</span></strong
      ><span> is identified, draw a circle around </span><strong
        ><span>3</span></strong
      ><span>
        of the left-most stress checkboxes, and notate them with &quot;SP&quot;.
      </span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Should an employee already have any standard stress points, those
        points will need to be shifted over to the available stress checkboxes
        to the right of stress points derived from
      </span><strong><span>Problems / Serious Problems</span></strong><span
        >.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>Finally, make sure to also document in the</span><strong
        ><span> Stress Related Circumstances </span></strong
      ><span>section, the nature of the </span><strong
        ><span>Problem </span></strong
      ><span>or</span><strong><span> Serious Problem</span></strong><span
        >.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>To be clear, any stress derived from a </span><strong
        ><span>Problem </span></strong
      ><span>or</span><strong><span> Serious Problem </span></strong><span
        >cannot be wiped clean from the daily rejuvenation that comes from a
        work day transitioning into the next.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong
        ><span
          >Problems must be addressed and resolved before the stress they cause
          may be recovered.</span
        ></strong
      >
    </p>
